@node "interviewe" "Interview mit Tim Corringham"
   
                        Interview mit Tim Corringham
   
                 Er und sein Team portieren Opera für Amiga
   
   
 *  FT:   Please tell us something about yourself and RamJam Consultants
   Ltd.  What have you done before getting in touch with Opera Software?
   
   * TC:I'm a software engineer with 17 years industrial experience.  I've
   worked   in  a  variety  of  positions,  from  programming  to  project
   management,  mostly  specialising  in  the development of compilers and
   related  tools.   A  little  over  5  years  ago  I  established Ramjam
   Consultants  in order to allow me to do more of the things I enjoy, and
   less  of  the administration that is necessary in the large companies I
   used to work for.
   
   I've  been  a  keen  Amiga  user since the A500 was released in the UK.
   Until  Commodore's  collapse,  I  was  a registered Amiga developer.  I
   still  use  Amigas  to  run  Ramjam  -  we have a ethernet network of 3
   A3000s, and an A4000.
   
   When  I  needed  parts to keep our A3000s running, I discovered that it
   was  hard  to  find  suppliers.  I was so impressed at the AmiFAST 3000
   ZIP-to-SIMM  adapter  that  I  decided  that Ramjam should sell this in
   Europe.   We  also  sell a few other items, but our main business is in
   software development.
   
   We  started  "adopting"  good orphaned Amiga freeware a couple of years
   ago,  and  we  support  programs  such  as  tcpdl  - a program that can
   download web sites very quickly.
   
   When I saw Opera I immediately thought what a good Amiga application it
   would make, and I wanted Ramjam to do the port.
   
 * FT:How did you get in touch with Opera Software?
   
   *  TC:Initially  I just e-mailed them.  Since then I've been to Oslo to
   talk face to face with them.
   
 *  FT:   Will  Opera  Amiga  have  full  functionality  compared to the
   original Opera for Windows(e.g.  Realaudio, Javascript, Java(in V4))?
   
   * TC:  Javascript certainly.  We're aiming to have the functionality as
   close  as  possible  to  the W95 Opera, but there may be some licencing
   issues  to  be  resolved for some things - these often take longer than
   the technical work.
   
   We'd very much like to port V4, but we have to get V3 done first!
   
 * FT:Will you use MUI for the Opera GUI?
   
   *  TC:No.   The  choice  of  GUIs  is  something that divides the Amiga
   community.   Not  everybody likes MUI, and it is also a little resource
   hungry.   We're  basing  the  interface  on  gtlayout, with some custom
   extensions.   It  gives  a  good  compromise  between  speed, size, and
   appearance.
   
 * FT:There are already three fine browsers available for the Amiga.  Do
   you think Opera has a real chance in the Amiga market?
   
   *  TC:   I  like  the  existing  Amiga browsers, but they are weak in a
   couple of important areas
   
   1)  stability  - whan you run a business on your Amiga you can't afford
   to have it crash when you're browsing.
   
   2)  yesterday's features - since the development teams are small (often
   1 person working in their spare time) there is no way that the existing
   browsers can incorporate new features as fast as they arise.
   
 * FT:Which features does Opera offer, which no other Amiga Browser has?
   
   *  TC:I  think  that  the  really  important feature is the size of the
   development  team.  With a large team developing Opera, and a team of 4
   working  part  time  just  to port it to the Amiga, new features should
   arrive on the Amiga much sooner.
   
   Of  course,  having  Opera available on a number of different platforms
   will  be an advantage too, especially for people that need to use other
   machines.
   
 * FT:  When will Opera Amiga be released?
   
   The  official  date  is  December  -  although  the  exact date will be
   determined  by  Opera  Software.   There will be updates on the Project
   Magic web pages whenever there is any news.
   
 * FT:  How much will Opera Amiga cost?
   
   * TC:Again, that's up to Opera Software to decide, but I'd expect it to
   be around the same price as Opera currently sells for, i.e.  $35.
   
 *  FT:   Will  there  be  a  PPC version of Opera Amiga(e.g.  for image
   decoding)?
   
   *  TC:   We'd  like  that,  but we'll have to see how development goes.
   Also, the PPC user base is still very small (around 4000 users) so we'd
   have to be careful about the effort we expend.
   
 *  FT:  What is your opinion on the Amiga OS 4.0 developer machine?  Is
   this an interesting perspective for you?
   
   *  TC:  Absolutely.  Although of course it is only a bridge to the even
   more exciting OS 5.0 machines!
   
 *  FT:  What is your opinion on the future plans of Amiga Inc.?  How do
   their plans influence your plans on future developments for the Amiga?
   
   *  TC:I must admit the announcement at WoA wasn't what I was expecting.
   However,  I  think that AI's plans are very exciting, and I don't think
   everyone  has  realised  the  impact  that the new generation of Amigas
   could  have  in  18 months.  We're now even more determined to increase
   the  Amiga  developments  that  we're involved in over the next year or
   two.
   
 * FT:Thank you for answering our questions.
   
    (Das Interview führte Mat Colton)


